  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What versions of the Bible are there?",
  "response": "The Bible has been translated into numerous versions over the centuries, each with its own approach to translation, theological perspective, and intended audience. Here are some of the most well-known versions:\n\n1. **King James Version (KJV)**: First published in 1611, this is one of the most famous English translations. It is renowned for its majestic literary style.\n\n2. **New International Version (NIV)**: First published in the 1970s, the NIV is known for its balance between accuracy and readability, making it one of the most popular modern translations.\n\n3. **English Standard Version (ESV)**: Published in 2001, the ESV aims for a word-for-word translation that is accessible and readable, maintaining literary excellence.\n\n4. **New American Standard Bible (NASB)**: Known for its literal translation, the NASB, first published in 1971, is highly regarded for its precision.\n\n5. **New Revised Standard Version (NRSV)**: Published in 1989, it is an update of the RSV and is widely used in academic settings and by many Christian denominations.\n\n6. **Revised Standard Version (RSV)**: An update of the American Standard Version, the RSV was first published in 1952 and is noted for its scholarship.\n\n7. **The Message (MSG)**: A contemporary paraphrase by Eugene Peterson, published in the 1990s. It focuses on readability and conveying the thought rather than a word-for-word translation.\n\n8. **New Living Translation (NLT)**: First published in 1996, the NLT is a thought-for-thought translation aimed at clarity and ease of understanding.\n\n9. **Holman Christian Standard Bible (HCSB)**: A modern English translation published in 2004 with an emphasis on accuracy and readability.\n\n10. **Contemporary English Version (CEV)**: Published by the American Bible Society in 1995, it is known for its simple, yet accurate, everyday language.\n\n11. **Good News Bible (GNB)**: Also known as the \"Good News Translation\" (GNT), it was first published in 1966 and is appreciated for its straightforward language.\n\n12. **New King James Version (NKJV)**: Published in 1982, this version updates the language of the KJV while maintaining its traditional style.\n\nThese are just a few of the many versions available. Each version has its own strengths and suitability depending on the reader\u2019s needs, whether for literary, devotional, scholarly, or casual reading.",
